00:00:01,508 --> 00:00:06,624
In this video I am going to talk about
perhaps the simplest kind of problem in

2
00:00:06,624 --> 00:00:12,882
time-dependent quantum mechanics, that is,
the problem of the sudden perturbations,

3
00:00:12,882 --> 00:00:17,757
which happens when a potential in
a quantum problem changes very fast as

4
00:00:17,757 --> 00:00:21,846
compared to all other relevant
time scales in the problem.

5
00:00:21,846 --> 00:00:29,200
So another term for such a sudden change
in the potential is a quantum quench.

6
00:00:30,350 --> 00:00:32,869
And this may happen, for instance,

7
00:00:32,869 --> 00:00:38,566
if we have a potential which changes very
rapidly from one form to a different form.

8
00:00:38,566 --> 00:00:43,500
So let's say here, for example,
I'm showing a harmonic oscillator, and

9
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:48,433
let's say for a negative time we have
a particle, let's say, just sitting

10
00:00:48,433 --> 00:00:53,292
here on a stationary state described
by the usual Gaussian wave function,

11
00:00:53,292 --> 00:00:56,455
which is the eigenfunction
of the ground state,

12
00:00:56,455 --> 00:01:00,423
the ground state wave function
of the harmonic oscillator.

13
00:01:00,423 --> 00:01:02,925
And let's imagine at t = 0,

14
00:01:02,925 --> 00:01:09,070
the frequency of the harmonic
oscillator potential changes rapidly.

15
00:01:09,070 --> 00:01:12,910
So it increases rapidly such that
it becomes a completely different

16
00:01:12,910 --> 00:01:14,350
potential now.

17
00:01:14,350 --> 00:01:16,450
So what kind of questions can we ask?

18
00:01:17,550 --> 00:01:21,600
Well, before asking questions,
let's see what's going on here.

19
00:01:21,600 --> 00:01:25,781
So the main sort of
insight in this problem is

20
00:01:25,781 --> 00:01:30,414
that while the potential
changes very rapidly,

21
00:01:30,414 --> 00:01:35,276
the wave function does not
have the time to change.

22
00:01:35,276 --> 00:01:40,394
So the wave-function right before
the quench is exactly equal to

23
00:01:40,394 --> 00:01:45,605
the wave-function right after the quench,
in the approximation

24
00:01:45,605 --> 00:01:51,204
of an infinitely fast or an infinitely
sudden quench of the potential.

25
00:01:51,204 --> 00:01:52,485
Let's say, in this case,

26
00:01:52,485 --> 00:01:57,020
from one harmonic oscillator frequency to
a different harmonic oscillator frequency.

27
00:01:57,020 --> 00:02:02,500
But another important insight is that
the quantum state that used to be a good,

28
00:02:02,500 --> 00:02:08,350
stable stationary ground state is no
longer an eignestate of our potential.

29
00:02:08,350 --> 00:02:09,490
But what is it?

30
00:02:09,490 --> 00:02:13,259
So this wave-function,
the old wave-function,

31
00:02:13,259 --> 00:02:18,690
is just some wave-function from the point
of view of the new Hamiltonian.

32
00:02:18,690 --> 00:02:23,041
So, for instance,
let me call this guy here, psi 0 (1),

33
00:02:23,041 --> 00:02:27,730
which refers to the ground state of
the old potential that we had for

34
00:02:27,730 --> 00:02:30,762
a negative, where t is smaller than zero.

35
00:02:30,762 --> 00:02:32,823
And now after we quench it, so

36
00:02:32,823 --> 00:02:37,614
this psi 0 (1) is no longer
an eigenstate of the new Hamiltonian.

37
00:02:37,614 --> 00:02:42,190
Let's say we have the Hamiltonian,
H2, when it acts on psi 0 (1),

38
00:02:42,190 --> 00:02:46,541
it's no longer equal to an energy
of anything times psi 0 (1), so

39
00:02:46,541 --> 00:02:53,180
it's no longer proportional to psi 0 (1),
so this state is no longer an eigenstate.

40
00:02:53,180 --> 00:03:00,000
What it is, though, as always, we can use
the eigenstates of the new Hamiltonian.

41
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:02,960
So we can use these
eigenstates as a basis.

42
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:08,800
So what we can do,
we can expand our wave function,

43
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:14,480
which was the eigenstate of the old
Hamiltonian, in terms of the coefficient's

44
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:19,670
here, let me call it C sub n, and
n in this case goes from 0 to infinity,

45
00:03:19,670 --> 00:03:22,245
in this particular case of
the harmonic oscillator.

46
00:03:22,245 --> 00:03:26,060
And this can be expanded in
terms of the wave functions

47
00:03:26,060 --> 00:03:28,980
of the new harmonic
oscillator Hamiltonian.

48
00:03:28,980 --> 00:03:31,520
But, in general,
these coefficients are all non-zero.

49
00:03:31,520 --> 00:03:37,399
So basically what happens after we do
this quench is that the wave-function,

50
00:03:37,399 --> 00:03:42,118
which used to be a nice,
pure state with a well defined energy,

51
00:03:42,118 --> 00:03:46,306
well defined frequency,
now becomes, essentially,

52
00:03:46,306 --> 00:03:51,053
a bunch of incoherent harmonics
with different frequencies.

53
00:03:51,053 --> 00:03:55,554
If I were to suggest a possible
classical analog of what happens here,

54
00:03:55,554 --> 00:03:59,980
imagine you have a guitar string and
you generated a pure frequency,

55
00:03:59,980 --> 00:04:05,016
a pure sound, with the natural frequency
of the string, and then you suddenly

56
00:04:05,016 --> 00:04:10,087
changed the length of the string, well,
just pinch it at a certain distance.

57
00:04:10,087 --> 00:04:13,497
So then you're going to generate all kinds
of new sounds, all kinds of harmonics,

58
00:04:13,497 --> 00:04:15,068
it's no longer going to be a pure sound.

59
00:04:15,068 --> 00:04:19,281
A similar thing is happening here,
but instead of the sound,

60
00:04:19,281 --> 00:04:24,060
instead of the strings, we are having
quantum states which become now

61
00:04:24,060 --> 00:04:27,260
a linear combination of
the new eigenstates.

62
00:04:27,260 --> 00:04:29,910
So an interesting illustration, perhaps,

63
00:04:29,910 --> 00:04:34,660
of physically relevant phenomenon that
can be discussed in this context here.

64
00:04:34,660 --> 00:04:41,240
So let's say, again,
let me go back to this original potential.

65
00:04:41,240 --> 00:04:46,070
Let's say we have many particles
sitting in the ground state.

66
00:04:46,070 --> 00:04:50,477
So this basically means that there is
