80
00:05:36,570 --> 00:05:40,130
in this case it's a harmonic oscillator,
but it's a completely general statement,

81
00:05:40,130 --> 00:05:43,320
any sudden change of
the potential always heats it up.

82
00:05:43,320 --> 00:05:45,330
So it doesn't matter whether
we increase the frequency or

83
00:05:45,330 --> 00:05:47,960
decrease the frequency,
if we, let's say, had

84
00:05:47,960 --> 00:05:51,730
the lowest energy state in the beginning
with the lowest possible temperature,

85
00:05:51,730 --> 00:05:55,770
let's say even zero, absolute zero in
this model, if we do the quench, so

86
00:05:55,770 --> 00:06:01,370
the particles are going to be
redistributed among all possible energies.

87
00:06:01,370 --> 00:06:04,290
And, eventually, they're going to
relax to a final temperature,

88
00:06:04,290 --> 00:06:06,950
which is always higher
than the original one.

89
00:06:06,950 --> 00:06:09,830
So this is an interesting phenomenon
that we can understand without any

90
00:06:09,830 --> 00:06:12,150
calculations, just by this discussion.

91
