112
00:07:52,824 --> 00:07:57,143
in the Landau-Lifshitz course
on theoretical physics for

113
00:07:57,143 --> 00:08:00,529
those of you who have
access to this material.

114
00:08:00,529 --> 00:08:05,750
And well, the problem itself
is quite straightforward.

115
00:08:05,750 --> 00:08:08,569
So to formulate the problem,
so let's say we have an atom.

116
00:08:08,569 --> 00:08:13,363
So for the sake of simplicity,
I'll be talking about the hydrogen atom.

117
00:08:13,363 --> 00:08:18,735
But in principle we can consider any atom,
including heavy atoms for

118
00:08:18,735 --> 00:08:25,230
which it's the most interesting due to
various applications in nuclear physics.

119
00:08:26,720 --> 00:08:30,920
And let's imagine that
a nucleus of this atom,

120
00:08:30,920 --> 00:08:35,855
which has its atomic electron or
electrons in its ground

121
00:08:35,855 --> 00:08:41,130
state receives a sharp impulse
which gives it a velocity v.

122
00:08:41,130 --> 00:08:45,633
So we kick it with the radiation or with
a hammer, or we drop it from an airplane,

123
00:08:45,633 --> 00:08:47,740
or whatever you want to think about.

124
00:08:47,740 --> 00:08:51,251
So and what we want to know is,
what's going to happen with the electron?

125
00:08:51,251 --> 00:08:56,416
So basically here the sharp sudden
perturbation is that initially,

126
00:08:56,416 --> 00:08:58,380
we have this atom at rest.

127
00:08:58,380 --> 00:09:00,870
And at certain moment of
time let's say t equals 0,

128
00:09:00,870 --> 00:09:05,090
this atom starts moving
with a certain velocity v.

129
00:09:05,090 --> 00:09:07,718
And as it does so, we want to see,
we want to follow it, and

130
00:09:07,718 --> 00:09:09,723
we want to see if
the electron gets excited.

131
00:09:09,723 --> 00:09:15,900
But how do we calculate the probability
for the election to get excited?

132
00:09:15,900 --> 00:09:20,370
That is to say that it would
go to an excited state with

133
00:09:20,370 --> 00:09:24,610
the higher quantum number or
the atom would even get ionized.

134
00:09:24,610 --> 00:09:27,601
That is to say that the electron
just leaves the atom and

135
00:09:27,601 --> 00:09:30,983
goes into the continuum, and
they just go two separate ways,

136
00:09:30,983 --> 00:09:33,273
the atom of the nucleus and the electron.

137
00:09:33,273 --> 00:09:37,489
So here, naively, it seems that
the potential doesn't really change,

138
00:09:37,489 --> 00:09:39,400
we don't quench the potential.

139
00:09:40,800 --> 00:09:45,575
But, if we look at this problem a little
closer, we see that, well the atom,

140
00:09:45,575 --> 00:09:49,991
when it receives this impulse or
this kick, so the atom starts moving.

141
00:09:49,991 --> 00:09:54,880
And the atom is the potential, which binds
the electron to it in the first place.

142
00:09:54,880 --> 00:09:59,630
So therefore, the potential in which the
electron is supposed to be bound starts

143
00:09:59,630 --> 00:10:03,670
moving, and so this is sharp change.

144
00:10:03,670 --> 00:10:06,456
But the wave function of the electron
does not have time to change.

145
00:10:06,456 --> 00:10:11,082
So if let's say the electron was here
in the vicinity of the lowest orbit, so

146
00:10:11,082 --> 00:10:14,336
it was localized in the vicinity
of the lowest orbit,

147
00:10:14,336 --> 00:10:16,240
it will just try to stay there.

148
00:10:16,240 --> 00:10:20,706
And the question we're asking is, whether
the atom, when it starts moving with

149
00:10:20,706 --> 00:10:24,330
a certain velocity, whether it
will carry the electron with it.

150
00:10:24,330 --> 00:10:26,234
Or whether it will leave it behind or

151
00:10:26,234 --> 00:10:30,426
maybe whether the electron will sort
of dissipate into higher energy states.

152
00:10:30,426 --> 00:10:33,774
So and for this, to solve this problem,

153
00:10:33,774 --> 00:10:39,388
what turns out to be useful is to
go into another frame of reference,

154
00:10:39,388 --> 00:10:42,800
which is moving together with the atom.

155
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:46,680
So essentially, we want just to
move together with the atom and

156
00:10:46,680 --> 00:10:50,200
write the wave function of the electron
in this new frame of reference.

157
00:10:50,200 --> 00:10:52,801
So, this is really the key
to solving the problem.

158
00:10:52,801 --> 00:10:58,114
Because in the frame of reference
moving together with the atom,

159
00:10:58,114 --> 00:11:01,021
the potential is exactly the same.

160
00:11:01,021 --> 00:11:04,670
The Coulomb potential to begin with
is the Coulomb potential here.

161
00:11:04,670 --> 00:11:09,380
And in this frame of reference the atom,
the nucleus itself, is static, but

162
00:11:09,380 --> 00:11:10,830
the electron now is moving.

163
00:11:10,830 --> 00:11:15,173
And so essentially, what we have to do, we
have to write the electron wave function

164
00:11:15,173 --> 00:11:18,538
after the quench, after well in this case,
it's not a quench.

165
00:11:18,538 --> 00:11:20,120
I'm sorry, I shouldn't have said that.

166
00:11:20,120 --> 00:11:26,100
After this sort of jolt of the atom, and
this wave function will have two pieces.

167
00:11:26,100 --> 00:11:30,000
So, the first piece is
going to be just this standard

168
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:34,500
ground state wave function of the hydrogen
atom, in the case of a hydrogen atom.

169
00:11:34,500 --> 00:11:36,610
And there will be a piece, a new piece,

170
00:11:36,610 --> 00:11:41,600
which is related to the velocity of
the electron moving with velocity v.

171
00:11:41,600 --> 00:11:43,125
So here, essentially it's a plane wave.

172
00:11:43,125 --> 00:11:47,799
So, a way to write the wave
function in the frame of reference

173
00:11:47,799 --> 00:11:52,656
moving with the nucleus is to write
it as a product of a localized

174
00:11:52,656 --> 00:11:56,984
wave function in the lowest
orbit times the plane wave.

175
00:11:56,984 --> 00:11:57,880
And here again,

176
00:11:57,880 --> 00:12:02,415
this mv is simply the momentum of
the electron in this frame of reference.

177
00:12:02,415 --> 00:12:06,655
And this is just the standard
plane wave expression.

178
00:12:06,655 --> 00:12:11,755
So now the final step is to calculate the
excitation probability of the electron,

179
00:12:11,755 --> 00:12:16,295
that is, to find the total
probability of the electron going to

180
00:12:16,295 --> 00:12:19,385
some higher energy state,
including the continuum states.

181
00:12:19,385 --> 00:12:23,470
And well, the good thing is that
we know the wave function now.

182
00:12:23,470 --> 00:12:26,860
So in this moving frame of reference,
